Statement of Purpose

The laws of most jurisdictions throughout the world automatically confer
exclusive Copyright and Related Rights (defined below) upon the creator and
subsequent owner(s) (each and all, an "owner") of an original work of
authorship and/or a database fix (each, a "Work").

Certain owners wish to permanently relinquish those rights to a Work for the
purpose of contributing to a commons of creative, cultural and scientific
works ("Commons") that the public can reliably and without fear of later
claims of infringement build upon, modify, incorporate in other works,
republish, display, perform, sublicense and distribute.

The creator of a Work may voluntarily surrender some or all of those rights to
the Work under the terms of the Creative Commons Zero ("CC0") Public Domain
Dedication. For more information on CC0, visit
http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/.

All Creative Commons works are made available for free under the Creative
Commons Public Domain Dedication (CC0). However, should a Work contain any
material (including code snippets) that is the intellectual property of a
third party, you must ensure that such material is licensed under terms that
permit use in a public domain work. For example, if code snippets are
included in a Work, the code snippets must be licensed under terms that
permit use in a public domain work. This includes ensuring that any license
notices are preserved. If you are uncertain, seek the advice of legal counsel.

